`al.clear()` will also clear the contents of the array list that you have just put into `aal`. This is because the array list in `aal` and the one referenced by `al` are the _same_ array list. Here are two ways you can fix this.

1. Create a new array list after adding to `aal`:

        for(int i=2;i&lt;6;i++)
        {
            al.add(i);
            if(i%2!=0)
            {
                aal.add(al);
                al = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            }
        }

2. Add a copy of `al` to `aal` (this is probably what you expected your code would do):

        for(int i=2;i&lt;6;i++)
        {
            al.add(i);
            if(i%2!=0)
            {
                aal.add(new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(al));
                al.clear();
            }
        }

Notice in both of these cases, I am creating new array lists with `new ArrayList&lt;&gt;`.

